defs.docs: Support for concurrent and parallel programming.

defs.name: epoch
defs.docs: Epoch-based memory management

defs.name: Atomic
defs.docs: Like `std::sync::atomic::AtomicPtr`.

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Create a new atomic pointer

defs.name: load
defs.value: fn <'a> (&self, ord: Ordering, _: &'a Guard) -> Option<Shared<'a, T>>
defs.docs: Do an atomic load with the given memory ordering.

defs.name: store
defs.docs: Do an atomic store with the given memory ordering.

defs.name: store_and_ref
defs.value: fn <'a> (&self, val: Owned<T>, ord: Ordering, _: &'a Guard) -> Shared<'a, T>
defs.docs:
Do an atomic store with the given memory ordering, immediately yielding
 a shared reference to the pointer that was stored.

defs.name: store_shared
defs.docs: Do an atomic store of a `Shared` pointer with the given memory ordering.

defs.name: cas
defs.value: fn (&self, old: Option<Shared<T>>, new: Option<Owned<T>>, ord: Ordering) -> Result<(), Option<Owned<T>>>
defs.docs:
Do a compare-and-set from a `Shared` to an `Owned` pointer with the
 given memory ordering.

defs.name: cas_and_ref
defs.value: fn <'a> (&self, old: Option<Shared<T>>, new: Owned<T>, ord: Ordering, _: &'a Guard) -> Result<Shared<'a, T>, Owned<T>>
defs.docs:
Do a compare-and-set from a `Shared` to an `Owned` pointer with the
 given memory ordering, immediatley acquiring a new `Shared` reference to
 the previously-owned pointer if successful.

defs.name: cas_shared
defs.value: fn (&self, old: Option<Shared<T>>, new: Option<Shared<T>>, ord: Ordering) -> bool
defs.docs:
Do a compare-and-set from a `Shared` to another `Shared` pointer with
 the given memory ordering.

defs.name: swap
defs.value: fn <'a> (&self, new: Option<Owned<T>>, ord: Ordering, _: &'a Guard) -> Option<Shared<'a, T>>
defs.docs: Do an atomic swap with an `Owned` pointer with the given memory ordering.

defs.name: swap_shared
defs.value: fn <'a> (&self, new: Option<Shared<T>>, ord: Ordering, _: &'a Guard) -> Option<Shared<'a, T>>
defs.docs: Do an atomic swap with a `Shared` pointer with the given memory ordering.

defs.name: Guard
defs.docs: An RAII-style guard for pinning the current epoch.

defs.name: pin
defs.docs: Pin the current epoch.

defs.name: unlinked
defs.docs:
Assert that the value is no longer reachable from a lock-free data
 structure and should be collected when sufficient epochs have passed.

defs.name: migrate_garbage
defs.docs: Move the thread-local garbage into the global set of garbage.

defs.docs: Like `Box<T>`: an owned, heap-allocated data value of type `T`.

defs.docs: Move `t` to a new heap allocation.

defs.name: into_inner
defs.docs: Move data out of the owned box, deallocating the box.

defs.name: Shared

defs.name: sync
defs.docs: Synchronization primitives.

defs.name: MsQueue
defs.docs: A Michael-Scott lock-free queue, with support for blocking `pop`s.

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Create a new, empty queue.

defs.name: push
defs.docs:
Add `t` to the back of the queue, possibly waking up threads
 blocked on `pop`.

defs.name: is_empty
defs.docs: Check if this queue is empty.

defs.name: try_pop
defs.docs: Attempt to dequeue from the front.

defs.name: pop
defs.docs:
Dequeue an element from the front of the queue, blocking if the queue is
 empty.

defs.name: TreiberStack
defs.docs: Treiber's lock-free stack.

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Create a new, empty stack.

defs.name: push
defs.docs: Push `t` on top of the stack.

defs.name: pop
defs.docs:
Attempt to pop the top element of the stack.
 **Deprecated method**, use try_pop

defs.name: try_pop
defs.docs: Attempt to pop the top element of the stack.

defs.name: is_empty
defs.docs: Check if this queue is empty.

defs.name: SegQueue
defs.docs:
A Michael-Scott queue that allocates "segments" (arrays of nodes)
 for efficiency.

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Create a new, empty queue.

defs.name: push
defs.docs: Add `t` to the back of the queue.

defs.name: is_empty
defs.docs: Judge if the queue is empty.

defs.name: try_pop
defs.docs: Attempt to dequeue from the front.

defs.name: chase_lev
defs.docs: A lock-free concurrent work-stealing deque

defs.name: Worker
defs.docs:
Worker half of the work-stealing deque. This worker has exclusive access to
 one side of the deque, and uses `push` and `try_pop` method to manipulate it.

defs.name: Stealer
defs.docs:
The stealing half of the work-stealing deque. Stealers have access to the
 opposite end of the deque from the worker, and they only have access to the
 `steal` method.

defs.name: Empty
defs.docs: The deque was empty at the time of stealing

defs.name: Abort
defs.docs:
The stealer lost the race for stealing data, and a retry may return more
 data.

defs.name: Data
defs.docs: The stealer has successfully stolen some data.

defs.name: Steal
defs.docs: When stealing some data, this is an enumeration of the possible outcomes.

defs.name: push
defs.docs: Pushes data onto the front of this work queue.

defs.name: try_pop
defs.docs:
Pops data off the front of the work queue, returning `None` on an empty
 queue.

defs.name: steal
defs.docs: Steals work off the end of the queue (opposite of the worker's end)

defs.name: deque
defs.docs: Creates a new empty deque

defs.name: set

Stores a new value in the `ArcCell`, returning the previous
 value.

defs.name: get

Scoped thread configuration. Provides detailed control over the properties and behavior of new
 scoped threads.

defs.name: name

Names the thread-to-be. Currently the name is used for identification only in panic
 messages.

defs.name: stack_size

defs.name: spawn
